column5:
After crossing the Dumbarton bridge, I headed out on the dirt levee trail towards Coyote Hills Park. After 1/2 mile, my tire treads started to get caked with mud, so I turned around. I didn't make it more than 1/10 mile back before my rear tire slipped out from underneath me and I fell to the side.You wouldn't think a fall from 3 feet onto dirt at 11 mph would be so bad. I've done worse many times playing sports and never had anything more than some scrapes. Anyway, my right hip broke, I had surgery; three titanium screws inserted, and now I'm on the mend. I'm walking with a cane now (April 5);  and hopefully back to normal in about 3 months.

The attached xray image is not me, but it is the one that I could find online that looks the closest to what the surgeon showed me.

For those outside the Bay Area, here's what the trail looks like: https://www.google.com/maps/@37.5223122,-122.1103263,3a,75y,169.85h,98.96t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sL4VlyJ955I3SmTQZesWWjA!2e0!7i13312!8i6656

column5:
"Everesting" is the name for a ride that climbs the elevation of Mt. Everest,  29,032 feet. The fastest Everesting was completed on March 23, 2021 by Ronan Mc Laughlin: 6 and 2/3 hours. I thought I could manage it in a time under 6 and 2/3 ... days. 

I did it! Thanks to Anne and David for riding along on some of the days. 

Photo album: https://photos.app.goo.gl/FsvtyBUALP4Jcbxs8

Day 1: Mt Diablo, 3406 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5033910490
Day 2: Kings + OLH, 4377 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5040552043
Day 3: Ring of Fire, 4544 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5046452853
Day 4: Kings + Tunitas, 4452 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5052061810
Day 5: OLH2, 4344 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5058469308
Day 6: West Alpine, 4400 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5064119006
Day 7: Mill Creek + Morrison, 3517 ft https://www.strava.com/activities/5070717729

Ronan Mc Laughlin rode a straight, steep stretch of road in Ireland that is 1/2 mile long and a 117 meter  climb (14% grade), which means he needed 76 laps, averaging 11.4 mph.

I averaged more like 7% grade, and wanted variety, so did different routes each day, and "wasted" time on flat parts between climbs. I ended up spending about 3 hours a day on hills and an hour or so a day getting to and from climbs. So overall, almost 4 times slower than Mc Laughlin, not counting the 20 hours of rest each day.

The site https://longtinyloop.com/ invites you to make a path that doesn't cross itself, and maximizes the ratio of distance traveled to path diameter. For this path:

Distance: 37.34 km
Diameter: 2.69 km
Ratio: 13.86

It takes a lot of concentration to not miss a turn (particularly because I was taking advantage of alleyways and "lanes" that are not clearly marked), and if you do miss a turn, you're doomed: like in the video game "Snake," you may be able to keep going for a bit, but before long you will intersect your path and lose the game.

Our crew set off on an expedition to find the lost passage from lower Huddart Park Rd to upper Huddart Park Rd via the elusive Chickadee Nature Trail, which wandrer.earth claims is an existing bike route. Here is the Captain's Diary:

Mile 14.4: we leave the friendly confines of the road and head out on a trail. The crew is optimistic.

Mile 14.5: it becomes clear that our map is inaccurate; our gps position does not align with the path on the map. It is rough singletrack; tough going on 28mm tires. Some of the crew mumble that we are unprepared and underbiked.

Mile 14.6: we are seriously on the wrong trail. Will the trail lead to a different, previously undiscovered route to upper Huddart Park Rd, bringing us  newfound fame?

Mile 14.8: the trail has doubled back, away from the road. Some of the crew members have a mutinous look. 

Mile 14.9: we arrive back at the starting road, having failed to find a passage. We continue on Huddart Park Rd the long way around, searching for the upper entrance to Chickadee Nature Trail. 

Mile 15.6: We find the entrance, clearly marked. The trail is smooth, flat, wide, clear, scenic doubletrack. Quite an improvement from the first, fruitless trail. The formerly-mutinous-looking crew let out a "three cheers for the captain," but they're not fooling anyone.

Mile 16.0: After a beautiful descent, we arrive at the junction where we took a wrong turn the first time around. Truly, the fork we took looks like the better road, and looks to be going in the right direction, but obviously it did end up being wrong. Still, the mission is a success.

0.49 new miles

-- From Wandrer.earth

It turns out the "Lane" quickly becomes a singletrack path, but I did make it all the way,helped by the fact that I brought a more appropriate bike with 2.8" tires.

My friend A J Jacobs set up a challenge: to climb the elevation to space in 2022. He has a tilting treadmill; I have my bike. Today I crossed the Krmn line into space100 km of climbing. (Incidentally, I also passed 5,000 miles of horizontal travel for the year on this ride.)

Now that I accomplished the goal of "climbing to space," I've started to look at Tilehunting. For the uninitiated (like I was a month ago), the OSM maps divide the world into roughly 1 mile x 1 mile tiles, and various sites let you track which tiles you have visited. 

The main objective is to form the maximum-size square of visited tiles. Living on a peninsula makes that hard, but I had an 11 x 11 square just below the bay, and by adding one more tile in Milpitas on this ride, I got to 12 x 12.

The secondary objective is the largest "cluster," which is defined as contiguous visited tiles where no tile is bordered by an unvisited tile on any of the four sides (which means that a corridor to connect two clusters must be at least 3 tiles wide, because the outside tiles don't count as part of the cluster). By getting one more tile in Milpitas on this ride, I merged South- and East-Bay clusters, increasing my max cluster from 295 to 380 tiles. I only got 2 new clusters on the 54 mile ride, but they were two strategic ones.

See statshunters.com or rideeverytile.com for more on Tilehunting.

Yesterday I "completed" Redwood City and Mountain View, according to wandrer.earth (which gives you credit if you reach 99% of the roads). 

Today I completed Palo Alto.  Although it is my home town, Palo Alto is difficult to complete (and no other Wandrer has done it) because of a pentathlon of challenges:

(1) MOUNTAINS: You may think of Palo Alto as hugging Route 101 by the Bay, but a thin slice of the city goes up to Skyline Boulevard, where there are some trails that require a mountain bike, not a road bike.

(2) SCARY TRAFFIC: There are some roads with lots of traffic, 45 MPH speed limit, and no shoulder whatsoever (such as the ramp from Alma to Oregon Expressway).

(3) MAP ERRORS: There is a mile-long path in Foothill park that is marked as accessible to bikes, but in fact it is not. That leaves very little margin of error for getting to 99% plus.

(4) SIGNS: Some places (such as the VA hospital) have closed off roads during covid. You need to either have ridden the road pre-covid, or be willing to sneak around the "do not enter" signs.

(5) SIZE: There are 300 miles of roads in Palo Alto.

https://content.rapha.cc/us/en/story/laels-ride-around-the-world so I was able to meet up when she passed through San Gregorio. column3: Foster City complete, San Mateo County 75%
column5:
I needed 0.3 miles to get to 75% of San Mateo County, and just 0.01 miles (53 feet!) to complete Foster City.  Got it done. 

0.47 new miles
Completed 75% of San Mateo County
 Completed Foster City
-- From Wandrer

If an electric vehicle can have MPG-equivalent measures, then so can my bike, and today I rode over 2000 mile-equivalents! Wandrer dot earth gives bonus miles for certain achievements, and today I harvested a bunch of them:

1470 bonus miles for riding 25% of Alameda County
263 bonus miles for riding 25% of Oakland
283 bonus miles for riding 75% of San Mateo County
10 bonus miles for completing 99% of Foster City
60 points for most miles in Alameda County this month
30 points for riding 30 new miles
2116 total mile-equivalent points for the day!

By getting the 25% achievement for Oakland, I can now say that I have the achievement for every city around the Bay, south of the Bay Bridge.

In October I realized that I was climbing up in the rankings for Wandrer points in California. I had 1600-something points and was about 15th place. But there were multiple cities and counties where I was getting close to big bonuses, so I rode those, and now Im in 7th place with 20,000+ points. It took me 12 years of GPS-recording riding to get the first 16,000 mile-equivalent points, and only 100 days to get the next 4,000! 

Thanks [strava://athletes/12153730/12]Craig Durkin  for making a great game/pastime in wandrer dot earth!
